States with topological order (TO) or symmetry-protected topological order (SPTO) exhibit novel collective behavior due to the presence of persistent entanglement. This entanglement makes such states, and sometimes even entire quantum phases, useful resources for quantum computation, with different types of quantum order usable for different computational tasks. States with TO have long-range entanglement which is well-adapted for quantum memories and topological quantum computation, while states with SPTO have short-range entanglement which is suitable for measurement-based quantum computation (MQC).

While the correspondence between SPTO and MQC resource quality has been well-studied in 1D spin chains, little is known about the practically relevant setting of 2D systems, which are necessary for universal quantum computation. One complication which arises in the 2D setting is the existence of two distinct types of SPTO: 2D states can possess either "weak" SPTO, of the same nature as the SPTO of 1D spin chains, or "genuine" 2D SPTO. Given this complication, two natural questions which arise in the 2D setting are:
What type of SPTO do canonical MQC resource states, such as the 2D cluster state, possess?
Can both types of SPTO be used for MQC? If so, can we identify advantages of one type over the other?

Although the 2D cluster and Union Jack states are both universal resource states, they can be usefully compared within the context of the Clifford hierarchy, where the latter is associated with a greater quantum gate complexity. We expect this to lead to computational advantages of genuine 2D SPTO over previously studied MQC resource states. Our work is explained in detail in [1].

Theorem 2: The Union Jack state with on-site symmetry possesses nontrivial 2D SPTO and trivial 1D SPTO. It is also a universal resource state for MQC, in that arbitrary quantum circuits can be efficiently simulated using only single-qubit measurements and feed-forward of measurement outcomes.
